Here are the five fixes for your .NET 10 upgrade:

---

### 1. `[InlineArray]` + explicit `[StructLayout(Size)]` â†’ assembly fails to load
In .NET 10, `[InlineArray]` structs **cannot** have an explicit `[StructLayout(Size = ...)]`. Remove the `StructLayout` attribute â€” the runtime infers the layout from the inline array:

```csharp
// Before (breaks at runtime)
[InlineArray(16)]
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]
public struct MyBuffer { private int _element0; }

// After
[InlineArray(16)]
public struct MyBuffer { private int _element0; }
```

### 2. `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` returns real filesystem names on Linux
Previously it returned generic values; now it returns actual names like `ext4`, `xfs`, `btrfs`. Update string comparisons:

```csharp
// Before â€” compared against generic/old values
if (driveInfo.DriveFormat == "ext")

// After â€” compare against actual filesystem type names
if (driveInfo.DriveFormat is "ext4" or "ext3" or "xfs" or "btrfs")
```

### 3. NU1510 â€” pruned direct references
NuGet now warns when a `<PackageReference>` is redundant because the package is already in the shared framework. **Remove** those explicit references from your `.csproj`:

```xml
<!-- Remove lines like this if the package is in the shared framework -->
<PackageReference Include="System.Text.Json" Version="10.0.0" />
```

### 4. Transitive NuGet vulnerability auditing
`dotnet restore` now audits **transitive** dependencies by default. Review the new vulnerability warnings and either:
- Update the transitive dependency (by updating the parent package)
- Or suppress with `<NuGetAuditMode>direct</NuGetAuditMode>` in your `.csproj` (not recommended â€” fix the vulnerabilities instead)

### 5. `FilePatternMatch.Stem` is now non-nullable
`Stem` changed from `string?` to `string`. Null checks will produce compiler warnings. Replace null checks with empty-string checks:

```csharp
// Before
if (match.Stem is null) { ... }

// After
if (match.Stem.Length == 0) { ... }
// or
if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(match.Stem)) { ... }
```

